description: Mg in calcite, mol%, 3-core stack: Mg percentage in calcite is used to reconstruct lacustrine paleohydrology and climate history. The Mg percentage in calcite rises during evaporative concentration of a lake because of increases in the [Mg2+]/ [Ca2+] ratio in lake water. This ratio rises during evaporation because of (1) Ca loss by precipitation and sedimentation of endogenic calcite in the evaporating water body and (2) rising salinity that concentrates dissolved Mg.

description: Detrended Mg in calcite, mol%, 3 core stack: Mg percentage in calcite is used to reconstruct lacustrine paleohydrology and climate history. The Mg percentage in calcite rises during evaporative concentration of a lake because of increases in the [Mg2+]/ [Ca2+] ratio in lake water. This ratio rises during evaporation because of (1) Ca loss by precipitation and sedimentation of endogenic calcite in the evaporating water body and (2) rising salinity that concentrates dissolved Mg.

basis: interpreted as higher organic matter linked to increased runnoff....
QC comments: Record of pluvials with an annual/winter season interpretation "These conditions include a significantly southward displaced, winter season polar front jet stream, its associated storm tracks, and moisture transport from the tropical North Pacific. Moreover, these conditions must persist on a near annual (winter season) basis for the duration of the lake            s existence. To develop and maintain decadal-to-multi-centennial scale lakes in the Mojave River sink requires atmospheric conditions that generate higher- than-average winter precipitation across the region on a recur- ring annual basis."

Fleitmann, D. ; Cheng, H. ; Badertscher, S. ; Edwards, R. L. ; Mudelsee, M. ; Goektuerk, O. M. ; Fankhauser, A. ; Pickering, R. ; Raible, C. C. ; Matter, A. ; Kramers, J. ; Tueysuez, O.
description: Stable isotope (carbon and oxygen) of stalagmite So-1 from Sofular Cave, Northern Turkey. 230Th dating of stalagmite So-1 was made on a multi-collector inductively coupled plasma mass spectrometer (MC-ICP-MS, Thermo-Finnigan-Neptune) at the Minnesota Isotope Laboratory, University of Minnesota (auxiliary material Table A1). Further 230Th dating on all stalagmites was done on a Nu Instruments MC-ICP-MS at the Geological Institute, University of Bern. Stable isotope analyses were performed on a Finnigan Delta V Advantage mass spectrometer equipped with an automated carbonate preparation system (Gas Bench-II) at the Institute of Geological Sciences, University of Bern. Precision of d13C and d18O measurements is 0.06     and 0.07     (1s-error) respectively.
